The script utility works best with commands that do not manipulate the screen.     "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/freebsd/freebsd-src/pulls/414",
    "id": 339709741,

    "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/freebsd/freebsd-src/issues/414",
    "number": 414,
    "state": "closed",
    "locked": false,
    "title": "Don't left-shift negative numbers in certain circumstances in the various fdlibm hypot() functions",
    "user": {
      "login": "jswalden",
      "id": 4139753,
      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjQxMzk3NTM=",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/4139753?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/jswalden",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "Various paths through `hypot(x, y)` will multiply `x` and `y` by a power of two, perform the calculation in a range where IEEE-754 provides greater precision, then undo the multiplication to determine the true result.  Undoing that multiplication is implemented as `t1*w`, where `t1=2**k`.\r\n\r\n`2**k` is often computed by taking the high word of `1.0`, then adding `k<<20` (for doubles or long doubles) or `k<<23` (for floats) to it, then overwriting that high word.  But when `k` is negative this left-shifts a negative value -- and that's undefined behavior in many editions of C and C++.\r\n\r\nThis patch should fix all `hypot` implementations to compute `2**k` without triggering this particular bit of undefined behavior.  I've only _very lightly_ tested out the `double` change, in SpiderMonkey's JavaScript engine; the other functions' changes have more or less only been eyeballed.  I am also unsure whether the particular ways of spelling things out here are stylistically preferred; the fdlibm code has all sorts of magic numbers in it, and few idioms for hiding them away behind structured access functions, so the desired idioms are not entirely obvious.  Careful examination appreciated!",
    "created_at": "2019-11-12T03:29:02Z",
    "updated_at": "2019-11-27T08:34:16Z",
    "closed_at": "2019-11-27T08:34:15Z",

    "id": 321009338,

    "number": 412,
    "state": "closed",
    "locked": false,
    "title": "Do not left-shift by a negative number (inducing undefined behavior in C/C++) in expm1/expm1f during intermediate computations that compute the IEEE-754 bit pattern for |2**k| for integer |k|",
    "user": {
      "login": "jswalden",
      "id": 4139753,
      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjQxMzk3NTM=",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/4139753?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/jswalden",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "The implementations of `expm1`/`expm1f` need to compute IEEE-754 bit patterns for `2**k` in certain places.  (`k` is an integer and `2**k` is exactly representable in IEEE-754.)\r\n\r\nCurrently they do things like `0x3FF0'0000+(k<<20)`, which is to say they take the bit pattern representing `1` and then add directly to the exponent field to get the desired power of two.  This is fine when `k` is non-negative.\r\n\r\nBut when `k<0` (and certain classes of input trigger this), this left-shifts a negative number -- an operation with undefined behavior in C and C++.\r\n\r\nThe desired semantics can be achieved by instead adding the possibly-negative `k` to the IEEE-754 exponent bias to get the desired exponent field, _then_ shifting that into its proper overall position.\r\n\r\n(Note that there are `SET_HIGH_WORD`/`SET_FLOAT_WORD` uses further down in each of these files that perform shift operations involving `k`, but by these points `k`'s range has been restricted to `2 < k <= 56`, and the shift operations under those circumstances can't do anything that would be UB.)\r\n\r\nThese patches seem to do the right thing for me in manually testing them out in Mozilla's SpiderMonkey JavaScript engine (which imports fdlibm for a bunch of its math operations).  But this is obviously delicate code, so extra care in reviewing these proposed changes is appreciated.  \r\n\r\n(In mildly related vein, see also https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd/pull/130 for a prior UB issue in fdlibm we stumbled across and submitted for upstream reviewing/fixing.  Also note that I just filed [an issue](https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd/pull/411) for this same problem in fdlibm's `exp`/`expf` functions.)",

    "locked": false,
    "title": "Do not left-shift by a negative number (inducing undefined behavior in C/C++) in exp/expf during intermediate computations that compute the IEEE-754 bit pattern for |2**k| for integer |k|",
    "user": {
      "login": "jswalden",
      "id": 4139753,
      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjQxMzk3NTM=",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/4139753?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/jswalden",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "The implementations of `exp`/`expf` need to compute IEEE-754 bit patterns for `2**k` in certain places.  (`k` is an integer and `2**k` is exactly representable in IEEE-754.)\r\n\r\nCurrently they do things like `0x3FF0'0000+(k<<20)`, which is to say they take the bit pattern representing `1` and then add directly to the exponent field to get the desired power of two.  This is fine when `k` is non-negative.\r\n\r\nBut when `k<0` (and certain classes of input trigger this), this left-shifts a negative number -- an operation with undefined behavior in C and C++.\r\n\r\nThe desired semantics can be achieved by instead adding the possibly-negative `k` to the IEEE-754 exponent bias to get the desired exponent field, _then_ shifting that into its proper overall position.\r\n\r\nThese patches seem to do the right thing for me in manually testing them out in Mozilla's SpiderMonkey JavaScript engine (which imports fdlibm for a bunch of its math operations).  But this is obviously delicate code, so extra care in reviewing these proposed changes is appreciated.  \r\n\r\n(In mildly related vein, see also https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd/pull/130 for a prior UB issue in fdlibm we stumbled across and submitted for upstream reviewing/fixing.  Also note that I'll shortly be filing [an issue](https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd/pull/412) for this same problem in fdlibm's `expm1`/`expm1f` functions.)",

    "body": "BASEDIR is used to check to ensure we check sources in the right place as outlined by https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd/commit/ba040f8c3494b8eb245b20efe57ad591fec5613e#diff-7d334bdfcbfcd070ed2c6a35ada63787.\r\nProblem is that when this function is called, BASEDIR is empty because we set it to empty while reading conffile. This change ensures that if basedir is specified in conffile, that is used, if not then command line argument\r\nis checked and if that is not present as well then we default to /. Came across this at https://github.com/iocage/iocage/issues/892.",

    "body": "Add [initial] functional tests for sendfile(2) as lib/libc/sys/sendfile\r\n  \r\nThese testcases exercise a number of functional requirements for sendfile(2).\r\n\r\nThe testcases use IPv4 and IPv6 domain sockets with TCP, and were confirmed\r\nfunctional on UFS and ZFS. UDP address family sockets cannot be used per the\r\nsendfile(2) contract, thus using UDP sockets is outside the scope of\r\ntesting the syscall in positive cases. As seen in \r\n`:s_negative_udp_socket_test`, UDP is used to test the sendfile(2) contract\r\nto ensure that EINVAL is returned by sendfile(2).\r\n\r\nThe testcases added explicitly avoid testing out `SF_SYNC` due to the\r\ncomplexity of verifying that support. However, this is a good next logical\r\nitem to verify.\r\n\r\nThe `hdtr_positive*` testcases work to a certain degree (the header\r\ntestcases pass), but the trailer testcases do not work (it is an expected\r\nfailure). In particular, the value received by the mock server doesn't match\r\nthe expected value, and instead looks something like the following (using\r\npython array notation):\r\n\r\n`trailer[:]message[1:]`\r\n\r\ninstead of:\r\n\r\n`message[:]trailer[:]`\r\n\r\nThis makes me think there's a buffer overrun issue or problem with the\r\noffset somewhere in the sendfile(2) system call, but I need to do some\r\nother testing first to verify that the code is indeed sane, and my\r\nassumptions/code isn't buggy.\r\n\r\nTODO items:\r\n1. Fix the header/trailer testcases.\r\n2. Implement proper linear probing for available ports when setting up sockets.\r\n3. Handle short recv(2)'s in `server_cat(..)`.\r\n4. Add `SF_SYNC` support.\r\n5. Add some more negative tests outside the scope of the functional contract.\r\n\r\nSubmitted by:   ngie\r\nSponsored by:   Netflix, Inc",

    "body": "/usr/sbin/audit(dist)?d are only installed if ${MK_AUDIT} == yes. Their\r\nsupporting scripts should only be installed in those instances as well.\r\n\r\nNoted in code review with asomers@.\r\n\r\nSubmitted by:\tngie\r\n\r\nTest Plan:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ cd /usr/src\r\n$ env make -C libexec/rc/rc.d -VAUDIT -VMK_AUDIT\r\n\r\nno\r\n$ env SRCCONF=/dev/null make -C libexec/rc/rc.d -VAUDIT -VMK_AUDIT\r\nauditd auditdistd\r\nyes\r\n\r\n$ make check-old | grep /etc/rc.d/audit\r\n/etc/rc.d/auditd\r\n/etc/rc.d/auditdistd\r\n$ sudo make delete-old\r\n # Only deleted /etc/rc.d/audit*\r\n$ rcorder /etc/rc.d/* >/dev/null\r\nrcorder: file `/etc/rc.d/nisdomain' is before unknown provision `ypxfrd'\r\nrcorder: file `/etc/rc.d/nisdomain' is before unknown provision `ypserv'\r\nrcorder: file `/etc/rc.d/nisdomain' is before unknown provision `ypbind'\r\nrcorder: requirement `ipfw' in file `/etc/rc.d/netwait' has no providers.\r\nrcorder: requirement `ipfw' in file `/etc/rc.d/NETWORKING' has no providers.\r\nrcorder: requirement `ypset' in file `/etc/rc.d/automountd' has no providers.\r\nrcorder: requirement `ypset' in file `/etc/rc.d/keyserv' has no providers.\r\nrcorder: requirement `ypset' in file `/etc/rc.d/quota' has no providers.\r\nrcorder: requirement `ipfw' in file `/etc/rc.d/securelevel' has no providers.\r\n```",

    "user": {
      "login": "ngie-eign",

      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjE1NzQwOTk=",

    },
    "body": "The problem with the logic prior to this commit was twofold:\r\n1. The wrong set of idioms (TAP-compatible) were being applied to the ATF\r\n   testcases when run, resulting in confusing ATF failure results on\r\n   setup.\r\n2. The cleanup subroutines were broken when the geom classes could not be\r\n   loaded as they exited with 0 unexpectedly.\r\n\r\nThe fixes changes the test code to source the class-specific configuration\r\n(conf.sh) once globally, instead of sourcing it per testcase and per cleanup\r\nsubroutine, and to call the ATF-specific setup subroutine(s) inline in\r\nthe testcases.\r\n\r\nThe refactoring done is effectively a no-op for the TAP testcases,\r\nmodulo any refactoring done to create common code between the ATF and\r\nTAP testcases.\r\n\r\nThis unbreaks the geli testcases converted to ATF in r327662 and r327683,\r\nand the gmirror testcases added in r327780, respectively, when the geom\r\nclass could not be loaded.\r\n\r\ntests/sys/geom/class/mirror/...:\r\nWhile here, ignore errors when turning debug failpoint sysctl off, which\r\ncould occur if the gmirror class was not loaded.\r\n\r\nSubmitted by: ngie\r\n\r\nTest Plan:\r\n\r\nBefore:\r\n```\r\n     * Test program: /usr/tests/sys/geom/class/eli/attach_test\r\n     * Result: broken: Premature exit; test case exited with code 0\r\n     * Start time: 2018-11-28T03:03:10.053697Z\r\n     * End time: 2018-11-28T03:03:10.083744Z\r\n     * Duration: 0.030s\r\n     * Execution context\r\n\r\nMetadata\r\n\r\n     * allowed_architectures =\r\n     * allowed_platforms =\r\n     * description = geli attach -d will cause the provider to detach on last close\r\n     * has_cleanup = true\r\n     * is_exclusive = false\r\n     * required_configs =\r\n     * required_disk_space = 0\r\n     * required_files =\r\n     * required_memory = 0\r\n     * required_programs =\r\n     * required_user = root\r\n     * timeout = 300\r\n\r\nStandard output\r\n\r\n 1..0 # SKIP could not load module for geom class=eli\r\n 1..0 # SKIP could not load module for geom class=eli\r\n\r\nStandard error\r\n\r\n geom: Invalid class name 'eli'.\r\n geom: Invalid class name 'eli'.\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter (the classes are not loaded):\r\n```\r\n$ sudo kyua test -k /usr/tests/sys/geom/class/Kyuafile\r\n...\r\neli/setkey_test:setkey  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=eli  [0.022s]\r\neli/setkey_test:setkey_readonly  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=eli  [0.035s]\r\n...\r\nmirror/8_test:main  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=mirror  [0.011s]\r\nmirror/9_test:main  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=mirror  [0.010s]\r\nmirror/sync_error:sync_read_error_2_disks  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=mirror  [0.040s]\r\nmirror/sync_error:sync_read_error_3_disks  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=mirror  [0.020s]\r\n...\r\nuzip/1_test:main  ->  skipped: could not load module for geom class=uzip  [0.010s]\r\n...\r\n79/79 passed (0 failed)\r\n$\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter (the classes are loaded by the testcases organically):\r\n```\r\n$ sudo kyua test -k /usr/tests/sys/geom/Kyuafile\r\nclass/concat/1_test:main  ->  passed  [0.090s]\r\nclass/concat/2_test:main  ->  passed  [0.276s]\r\nclass/eli/attach_test:attach_d  ->  passed  [2.206s]\r\nclass/eli/attach_test:attach_r  ->  passed  [0.071s]\r\nclass/eli/attach_test:nokey  ->  passed  [0.052s]\r\nclass/eli/configure_test:configure_b_B  ->  passed  [0.196s]\r\nclass/eli/delkey_test:delkey  ->  passed  [0.255s]\r\nclass/eli/delkey_test:delkey_readonly  ->  passed  [0.074s]\r\nclass/eli/detach_test:detach_l  ->  passed  [2.216s]\r\nclass/eli/init_test:init  ->  passed  [8.953s]\r\nclass/eli/init_test:init_B  ->  passed  [0.177s]\r\n...\r\n```",

    "body": "Prior to this commit, `mfiutil show progress` would print out the time in seconds forcing\r\nthe user to convert the time to a easier to rationalize quantity. Given that RAID rebuilds\r\nsometimes take on the order of hours or days, it is more user friendly to print out the\r\nelapsed time in a humanized format, similar to how the ETA time is printed out.\r\n\r\nBug:\t225993\r\nSubmitted by:\tEnji Cooper <yaneurabeya@gmail.com>",

    "locked": false,
    "title": "`atan2(y, x)`'s special case for `x == 1.0` (in which case the result must be `atan(y)`) is unnecessarily complicated",
    "user": {
      "login": "jswalden",
      "id": 4139753,
      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjQxMzk3NTM=",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/4139753?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/jswalden",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/jswalden/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "As a component of `atan2(y, x)`, the case of `x == 1.0` is farmed out to `atan(y)`.  The current implementation of this comparison is vulnerable to signed integer underflow (that is, undefined behavior), and it's performed in a somewhat more complicated way than it need be.  Change it to not be quite so cute, rather directly comparing the high/low bits of `x` to the specific IEEE-754 bit pattern that encodes `1.0`.\r\n\r\nNote that while there are three different e_atan* files in the relevant directory, only this one needs fixing.  `e_atan2f.c` already compares against the full bit pattern encoding `1.0f`, while `e_atan2l.c` uses bitwise-ands/ors/nots and so doesn't require a change.\r\n\r\n(I ran into this in Mozilla's SpiderMonkey embedding of fdlibm, where a test of the behavior of `Math.atan2(1, -0)` triggered clang's signed-overflow-sanitizer runtime error.)",
    "created_at": "2018-02-13T04:52:59Z",

    "body": "OpenSSL\r\n\r\n\"dead meat belongs in frying pans or ovens\" -- xmj, sorry, but I'm sure you'll agree with this.\r\n\r\nFor a start, it's extremely unlikely that anyone is going to try to compile FreeBSD with Microsoft Visual C++ 5.0.\r\n\r\nSecondly, there's no logical cause and effect here. The function the code tries to communicate with (defined here: <https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/ms647550(v=vs.85).aspx>) can't see this variable. If it can, it can only do so by inspecting some hard-coded value from \"the stack\" or something \"magical\" (A.K.A. undefined behaviour). That makes this a nightmare to maintain, as introducing new variables before it will cause it to break, for a compiler nobody even uses anymore!\r\n\r\nFinally, throughout my research (yes, I did do research, contrary to the assumption otherwise), I found no evidence that this \"hack\" would resolve the problem. I crafted searches with different combinations of keywords such as \"MSVC++ 5.0\", \"printf\", \"double\", \"MT\" ... and even though I found evidence that the functions (on Windows, which is unimportant) indeed don't support floating points, I could find no other reference to this \"hack\" or \"work-around\" (those two are keywords, too, in case you'd like to try to verify my research).",

Calculate the tsc difference\r\n3. Reboot the system to get more tsc difference samples of the for loop.\r\n\r\nHere is my test result. I reboot the system 4 times for each sorting algorithm and the average of tsc difference are\r\nbubble sort: 7,220,292\r\nselection sort: 3.976,695\r\n\r\nSelection sort takes only 55% of the time compared to bubble sort.",

    "body": "Add test cases to reproduce all the problems (and then some)\r\nnoted in bug 218512.\r\n\r\nAllow setting passphrases and changing iterations in all cases\r\nexcept when two passphrases are set or being set. In that case,\r\ndisallow changing iterations.\r\n\r\nModify the behavior of setkey's '-i' to be deterministic. If a\r\nuser uses setkey and does not specify '-i', geli will find how\r\nmany iterations it can do in 2 seconds. It is possible for\r\nseparate invocations of setkey to come up with different\r\niterations, which could result in a setkey failure because\r\niterations is not allowed to be changed. This is fixed by\r\nusing the iterations value from the metadata if it has already\r\nbeen set, and then falling back to the calculation if no\r\niterations have been set in the metadata.\r\n\r\nUpdate the geli man page to reflect the above changed behavior.\r\n\r\nAdd the md_passphrases field to the metadata and increase the geli\r\nversion to v8. This allows geli to know for certain if a passphrase\r\nis set on the provider. The current implementation uses\r\nmd_iterations for this, but that only means a passphrase has been\r\nset at some point in the past. The metadata will automatically be\r\nupdated from v7 to v8 on the first metadata disk write.\r\n\r\nAdding md_passphrases has a side effect of aligning the remaining\r\nmetadata fields to 4 bytes, which should be better than the odd\r\nbyte alignment they currently have.\r\n\r\nUse the md_passphrases field to determine if a passphrase is set on\r\na provider.\r\n\r\nUse the md_passphrases field to determine if no passphrases are\r\nremaining on a provider and the iterations field in the metadata\r\ncan be cleared.\r\n\r\nFix geli dump to output iterations correctly. Add md_passphrases\r\nto dump.",

    "body": "`#define TWS_MAX_NUM_LUNS`\r\ndefines the maximum number of LUN's on the device and to my knowledge it shouldn't be limited to only 16 LUN's. In my config it was provoking problems because not all the disks (volumes) were detected. I changed the value to 32 in my config and everything seems to work now. However, I think the value should be 255.\r\n\r\nI am not aware of the reason why it was 16 in the first place.",

    "body": "This mirrors GNU xargs -P0 feature and increases portability of\nscripts that use it. There are a couple of differences though:\n o This change accepts negative numbers as well as 0 to mean the\n   same thing, which is consistent with other FreeBSD xargs options\n o This change sets number of parallel commands to maxargs instead\n   of some *_MAX macro: this should almost always be what the user\n   actually wants to do and increases performance by a lot.\n\nThe same patch is uploaded to Bugzilla #199976, which can be\nclosed if this is merged.\n",

    "body": "- Move cr_canseeinpcb to sys/netinet/in_prot.c in order to separate the\n  INET and INET6-specific code from the rest of the prot code\n  (It is only used by the network stack, so it makes sense for it to live\n  with the other network stack code.)\n- Move cr_canseeinpcb prototype from sys/systm.h to netinet/in_systm.h\n- Rename cr_seeotheruids to cr_canseeotheruids and cr_seeothergids to\n  cr_canseeothergids, make them non-static, and add prototypes (so they\n  can be see/called by in_prot.c functions.)\n- Remove sw_csum variable from ip6_forward in ip6_forward.c, as it is an\n  unused variable.\n- Add generic socket ioctl group (iocgroup) handling\n  - Allows for registering a group with the socket layer instead of needing\n    network stack-specific code in generic socket code\n  - iocgroups are handled similar to domains (all iocgroups must be registered\n    before finalization - to avoid requiring additional locking to get pushed\n    into a number of places in the kernel)\n  - Register interface iocgroup ('i')\n    - Moves call to ifioctl into the soiocg_ioctl member of iocgroup structure\n  - Register router iocgroup ('r')\n    - Moves call to rtiocl_fib to new function rtioctl_socket, which is the\n      soiocg_ioctl member of the iocgroup structure\n\nSubmitted by:   Steve Kiernan stevek@juniper.net\nObtained from:  Juniper Networks, Inc.\n",

This was encountered in _cpuset.h where BITSET_DEFINE(_cpuset, CPU_SETSIZE); on line 50 (rev 23b61e792eee74f3d6bdaf0ec6d265e6c70d7d3d ) results in a compilation error (ISO C does not allow extra ';' outside of a function) when compiling code that calls cpuset.h with the -pedantic-errors flag.\n",

    "body": "Hi All,\n\nI`ve noted that ngets() from libstand starts consuming CPU like mad when\nEOF appears on stdin. I see this issue with bhyveload when forwarding \"user input\" over pipe.\nHere is the simpliest program to reproduce:\n\ncat > ./bget.c\n# include <stdint.h>\n# include <unistd.h>\n# include <stdio.h>\n# include <sys/file.h>\n\nint main()\n{\n        char str[512];\n\n```\n    for (;;) {\n            ngets(str, sizeof(str));\n            if (str[0] == '\\n')\n                    break;\n    }\n    return 0;\n```\n\n}\n\n$ echo \"balbalbalabl\" | ./bget &\n$ \n\nYou will see bget consuming CPU in ngets() reading EOF, basically because getchar()\nreturns EOF again and again. Suggested patch fixes the problem.\n",

    "title": "don't zero the IP TOS bits on mbufs that need checksumming",
    "user": {
      "login": "Seb-LineRate",
      "id": 3513216,
      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjM1MTMyMTY=",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/3513216?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",

      "html_url": "https://github.com/Seb-LineRate",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/Seb-LineRate/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/Seb-LineRate/following{/other_user}",

      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/Seb-LineRate/orgs",

      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/Seb-LineRate/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/Seb-LineRate/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "body": "On mbufs that don't have the CSUM_DATA_VALID flag set, tcp_input()\nneeds to compute the TCP checksum itself.\n\nThe TCP checksum includes some but not all fields from the IP header.\n\ntcp_input() zeroes the fields of the IP header that are not to be\nincluded in the checksum, then checksums the entire packet (IP\nheader, TCP header, and TCP data), then restores the IP header\nfields it will need later.\n\nThe bug that this commit fixes is that the IP TOS field was not\nrestored, so the later read of it returned a zeroed byte instead\nof the incoming packet's actual TOS value.\n",
    "created_at": "2014-10-29T21:27:07Z",
